## Goal
Replace the categorical `error_type` value in the theme JS error reporter (`error` | `rejection`) with the actual JS class name when available (`TypeError`, `ReferenceError`, `SyntaxError`, etc.). Same-origin errors expose `e.error.name`; cross-origin errors stay redacted to the literal "error" string.

After the GTM JS error pipeline fix shipped (l3g, commit c03ab92), the dashboard JS errors section now surfaces real diagnostic values — but only as 2 buckets ("error" / "rejection"). Capturing `e.error.name` for first-party errors makes the dashboard 10× more useful for debugging actual theme bugs.

## Target file
- `layout/theme.liquid` — single file. Single function: the `addEventListener('error', ...)` handler near line 625.

## What to do

Find this block (current implementation):
```liquid
addEventListener('error', function (e) {
  var src = (e.filename || '') + ':' + (e.lineno || 0) + ':' + (e.colno || 0);
  send('error', e.message, src);
}, { capture: true });
```

Change `send('error', ...)` to use `e.error.name` when available, falling back to the literal "error" for cross-origin (where `e.error` is null due to browser security redaction):

```liquid
addEventListener('error', function (e) {
  var src = (e.filename || '') + ':' + (e.lineno || 0) + ':' + (e.colno || 0);
  var t = (e.error && e.error.name) ? e.error.name : 'error';
  send(t, e.message, src);
}, { capture: true });
```

Do NOT change the `unhandledrejection` handler — keep `send('rejection', ...)` literal there. Promise rejections don't have a meaningful `.error.name`; the categorical "rejection" bucket is fine.

## Invariants to preserve
- The existing MAX_ERRORS counter, message + source slicing (200 / 100 chars), and dataLayer push shape stay unchanged.
- `e.error` access is conditional (`e.error && e.error.name`) — never throw on missing `e.error`.
- The `'rejection'` bucket for unhandled promise rejections stays intact.

## How to verify
After live push:
1. In storefront DevTools console, run: `throw new TypeError("test-typeerror-2026-05-10")`. Then `dataLayer.filter(e => e && e.event === 'hairmnl_js_error').slice(-1)`. Expect: `error_type: "TypeError"` (NOT "error").
2. Run: `Promise.reject(new Error("test-rejection")).catch(()=>{}); setTimeout(()=>Promise.reject(new Error("uncaught")), 0)`. The uncaught one should show `error_type: "rejection"`.
3. Wait 24h, refresh dashboard — JS errors section now shows `TypeError`, `ReferenceError`, etc. for first-party errors. Cross-origin stays as "error".

## Goal
Defer LoyaltyLion SDK loading to first user interaction (scroll, click, or tap) instead of loading eagerly at DCL. Saves ~50-269KB on every initial pageload critical path. LoyaltyLion launcher button doesn't appear until the SDK loads, but it's not visible above-the-fold and isn't needed for first paint.

Per latest dashboard data (2026-05-09 PSI snapshot), `sdk-static.loyaltylion.net` contributes 269KB to mobile pageload. The launcher widget is a UX feature; lazy-loading on first interaction is the standard pattern.

## Target file
- `snippets/loyaltylion.liquid` — single file. The existing snippet (58 lines) constructs `window.loyaltylion` config + emits the LoyaltyLion SDK script tag conditionally for `customer.has_account`.

DO NOT modify `layout/theme.liquid` (the `{% include 'loyaltylion' %}` call at line 676 stays unchanged).

## What to do

Read `snippets/loyaltylion.liquid` first to understand the current structure. The existing logic:
1. Conditional: only emits SDK config + script if `customer != nil and customer.has_account`.
2. Sets up `window.loyaltylion` config object (token, customer.id, hash, etc.).
3. Emits `<script src="https://sdk-static.loyaltylion.net/...">`.

Modify so that the existing config object setup happens immediately at DCL (cheap — just a JS object), but the SDK `<script>` tag injection is deferred until the first user interaction event (scroll, click, touchstart, mousemove). Pattern:

```liquid
{% if customer != nil and customer.has_account %}
  <script>
    // Existing config setup unchanged
    window.loyaltylion = { token: "...", customer: { id: "...", email: "..." }, ... };

    // Lazy-load SDK on first interaction (saves ~269KB on critical path until user engages)
    (function() {
      var loaded = false;
      function loadSDK() {
        if (loaded) return;
        loaded = true;
        var s = document.createElement('script');
        s.async = true;
        s.src = 'https://sdk-static.loyaltylion.net/static/v3/loyaltylion.js'; // or whatever the existing src is
        document.head.appendChild(s);
      }
      var events = ['scroll', 'click', 'touchstart', 'mousemove', 'keydown'];
      var opts = { once: true, passive: true, capture: true };
      events.forEach(function(ev) {
        window.addEventListener(ev, loadSDK, opts);
      });
      // Safety net: load after 8 seconds even if no interaction (some users land + don't interact)
      setTimeout(loadSDK, 8000);
    })();
  </script>
{% endif %}
```

Use the EXACT script src + config that's currently in the snippet (read the existing snippet first to extract these). Do not invent URLs.

## Invariants to preserve
- The conditional gate (`customer.has_account`) stays — no SDK for guests/logged-out users.
- The customer config object (id, email, hash, points, etc.) is set up immediately so when the SDK eventually loads, it has its config.
- The 8-second timeout safety net ensures the launcher appears even for users who don't interact (e.g. landing page bounce).
- All event listeners use `{ once: true, passive: true, capture: true }` so they auto-remove after first fire and don't slow scrolling.

## How to verify
After live push:
1. Open storefront in incognito Brave with DevTools Network tab open. Sign in as a test customer first (LoyaltyLion only loads for authenticated).
2. Reload the page. In Network tab, filter by `loyaltylion` — initially NO requests should fire.
3. Scroll the page once. Now `sdk-static.loyaltylion.net/.../loyaltylion.js` should fire.
4. The LoyaltyLion launcher widget should appear after a brief delay.
5. Click the rewards button — points display + history should work.

## Risk + rollback
Medium risk because LoyaltyLion is revenue-relevant (loyalty points → repeat purchases). The 8-second safety-net timeout reduces risk to near-zero — even if a user never interacts, the SDK loads ~8s in.

Rollback path: revert the change. The original snippet remains in git history.

